<DOC><DOCNO> AP891109-0137 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1457EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-Haiti     11-09 0156</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Haiti,150</SECOND><HEAD>US Concerned about Arrests of Haitian Activists</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. Embassy in Haiti has expressedconcern to Haitian officials about the arrests of three peopleaccused of plotting the overthrow of the government, the StateDepartment said Thursday.   Deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said the embassy believes thatthe three, based on their appearance on television after theirarrests, were mistreated.   ``The United States government urges that the government ofHaiti ensure that any detainees are treated in strict accordancewith Haitian law with respect to their civil and human rights,'' hesaid.   On Nov. 1, Haitian authorities detained Evans Paul, leader ofthe Committee for Democratic Unity; Jean-Auguste Mesyeux, secretarygeneral of the Autonomous Confederation of Haitian Workers; andEtienne Marino, a leader of the Popular Organization of September17.   The State Department said a general strike Tuesday and Wednesdayto protest the alleged mistreatment of the three was widelyobserved.</TEXT></DOC>